Use of priors to enforce structured sparsity¶

Authors: Scott Sievert , Ian Kinsella , Blake Mason

Introduction¶

The objective of this lab is to demonstrate the value of methods that employ knowledge of structured sparsity in real life classification problems. Knowledge of structured sparsity means that we know our we know that our non-zero coefficients follow a certain pattern. In this lab, we’ll focus on the knowledge that our non-zero coefficients probably lie in certain regions.

Throughout this course, we have seen and experimented with different methods to exploit prior knowledge about how our solution should appear. The simplest of these was the assumption that the true solution should have low energy (a small L2 or Euclidean norm). To this end, we motivated the idea of Tikhonov regularization as a method for enforcing this constraint:

$$x = \arg \min_x ||y – Ax||_2^2 + \lambda ||x||_2^2$$

In this case, the extra L2 penalty enforces the energy constraint and $\lambda$ controls the tradeoff between fitting our data, represented in the $\arg \min_x ||y – Ax||_2^2$ term, and achieving a low energy solution represented by $||X||_2^2$.

As we progressed further in the class, we introduced the idea of sparsity and demonstrated some cases where we may prefer a sparse solution to a low energy one. An example of this was the breast cancer dataset where we had a list of genes as well as labels indicating whether or not a person has breast cancer. In this instance, we had many more genes than patients, making our problem highly underdetermined making regularization necessary to find a unique solution. We would expect that our solution should select a few genes to apply most of its weight to but zero the majority that are unrelated to breast cancer. The solution reflects this assumption is as follows.

$$x = \arg \min_x ||y – Ax||_2^2 + \lambda ||x||_1$$

We can think of this $\ell_1$ norm as the sum of elements. That is, $||x||_1 = \sum_i |x_i|$. A way to minimize this is to make many of the individual elements 0. Alternatively, we can draw pictures in two dimensions of all possible solutions and the obtained solutions. We can see that the $\ell_1$ ball minimizes distance between the possible solution and the norm ball. This is illustrated by the interactive widget below:

To achieve this, we applied the LASSO method (squared error and L1 penalty) and then solved the minimization using Iterative Soft-Thresholding (ISTA). ISTA zeroes out coefficients whose values are within a user defined parameter on either side of zero. Therefore, genes (features) corresponding to these smaller weights are discounted entirely in determining the classification. The user can control the degree to which we enforce sparsity by changing the value of $\lambda$.

The assumption of sparsity is well suited to the breast cancer dataset, but for other datasets, other sparsity assumptions may be better suited. In this lab we will motivate and implement different methods to exploit different sparsity priors in datasets where assuming sparsity alone may not be well suited for the classification task. To do this, we will introduce the proximal gradient method and derive the Iterative Soft Thresholding Algorithm (ISTA). We will also take advantage of gradient descent to converge to solutions with either no analytical form or whose closed form solution is prohibitively complex to calculate, such as large matrix inversions.

Background¶

Structured Sparsity and Priors¶

Throughout this course, we often have known certain information regarding our dataset and its generation. Even it we do not know things absolutely, we may wish to make certain assumptions that will be reflected in the type of answer we compute. Facts about the data that we know a priori are known as priors. In the same sense as the word’s use in the literature of probability and random processes, a prior can be thought of as a variable for which we know absolutely or relatively its value ahead of time. In the context of machine learning, this equates to properties that we know or expect the solution to possess. Examples of priors include the assumption of sparsity or the assumption of low energy in the solution.

Priors can be thought of as using information that is known about the signal. For example, when trying which genes are important for the cause we know from biological intuiton that there are only a few genes that are important.

In the case we'll investigate, we might know that the non-zero coefficients tend to be structured together. We'll be investigating how we can use that information.

Proximal Gradients: How¶

We can represent a large class of loss functions that enforce a prior as $$\phi(x) = F(x) + R(x)$$ is desired where $F, R : \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow\mathbb{R}$. Typically, $F$ is some error function representing data consistency, $R$ is some regularizer that we wish to use to enforce our prior(s) and $\lambda$ controls the tradeoff between the two objectives. For example, $F$ could be the least squares loss $F(x) = ||y - Ax||$ and the regularizer could be the Tikhonov regularization parameter, $\lambda ||x||_2^2$. With a given loss function $\phi(x)$, we wish to compute the argument that achieves its minimum.

This section will treat $F$ and $R$ to be general functions that obey specific properties. $F$ will be convex, continuous and differentiable with a Lipschitz continuous gradient and $G$ will be a convex, lower semicontinuous and possibly nondifferentiable.

This proximal gradient method takes a step to minimize $L$ then uses the output to minimize $R$. It does this in a loop, and makes intuitive sense because our function involves a sum of nonnegative values (one way to make the sum small is to make each individual term small). This idea of alternating minimization is widespread and relates to biconvex optimization.

Thus, it is important to consider the proximity operator. While minimizing the above function, we will be optimizing for $F$ then for $R$ in a loop. To do this, we will take a step in the gradient direction of $F$ then project back into the space of acceptable solutions by using the proximity operator.

The proximity operator is important because $x^\star$ is a minimizer to $F(x) + R(x)$ if and only if $x^\star = \textrm{prox}_{\gamma R} (x^\star - \gamma \nabla F(x^\star))$ where $\gamma > 0$ is any positive real number. For the formal justification behind this, see 0.

This means that the iterations proceed as follows:

At iterate $k$ with $x_{k-1}$ being the result of the previous iteration, compute $$\begin{align} z &= x_{k-1} - \tau \nabla F(x_{k-1}) \\ x_k &= \textrm{prox}_{\tau R}(z) \end{align}$$

where $\tau > 0$ is some stepsize that must obey the convergence criterion of $F$ (for least squares loss, $\tau < 1 / ||A||_2^2$).

This method can be accelerated. The step size $\tau$ may change depending on the iteration $k$, which results in the Fast Iterative Soft Thresholding Algorithm (FISTA) 7 and the Fast Adaptive Shrinkage/Thresholding Algorithm FASTA 6. There may be additional priors known and there may be further enhancements 1 3 5.

Warmup¶

We would like to minimize the function $$\phi(x) = L(x) + \lambda R(x)$$ Typically, $L : \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow\mathbb{R}$ is a differentiable loss function that represents the distance from the observed data and $R : \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow\mathbb{R}$ is some non-differentiable function that acts as a regularizer. This imposes some structure on estimated signal, typically sparsity of minimum energy.

One method to solve these problems is the [proximal gradient method]. In this method alternate between optimizing for the $x$ that minimizes the current estimate for $L$ and $R$. In words, the proximal gradient method takes a step in the gradient of $L$ then ensures the estimate found lies in the feasible solution set by feeding the result into a proximal operator.

Lasso¶

We will step through the derivation for the proximal operator for lasso. We will ask the reader to use this derivation for the questions we ask.

Loss function¶

As covered in class, the gradient of the squared error loss function is $$\nabla L(x) = -2A^T(y - Ax)$$

Prox operator¶

Theorem: For minimizing $\phi(x) = ||y - Ax||^2_2 + \lambda||x||_1$, the proximal operator is

$$\textrm{prox}_\lambda(x) = \textrm{sign}(z) \left(\left|z\right| - \frac{\lambda}{2}\right)_+$$

Proof: The prox operator for lasso is defined to be

$$\begin{align} \textrm{prox}_\lambda(z) &= \arg \min_x ||x - z||_2^2 + \lambda ||x||_1\\ &= \arg\min_x \sum_i (x_i - z_i)^2 + |x_i| \end{align}$$

meaning we can minimize each individual term separately.

$$\phi_{i, \lambda}(z) = (x_i - z_i)^2 + \lambda |x_i|$$$$\nabla\phi_i(z) = 2 (x_i - z_i)^2 + \lambda\textrm{sign}(x_i)$$

using the subgradients and defining $\textrm{sign}(x) \in [-1, 1]$. Because we know that $\textrm{sign}(x_i) = \textrm{sign}(z_i)$, we can instead write this as

$$\nabla \phi_i(z) = 2 (x_i - z_i)^2 + \lambda\textrm{sign}(z_i)$$

To see help see this more clearly, this is the scalar case. This function, $\phi(x_i)$ is similar to a parabola when $\lambda \approx 0$ which means that $\widehat{x}_i \approx z_i$. When $\lambda$ becomes larger, the minima shifts but is never less than 0; the minima is obeys $\textrm{sign}\left(\widehat{x}_i\right) = \textrm{sign}(z_i)$. To illustrate this fact, we have provided plots in the figure below.

In [4]:
Image(filename='implementation/prox_scalar.png', width=500)

$$\begin{align} \nabla \phi_i(x) &= 2 (x_i - z_i)^2 + \lambda\textrm{sign}(x_i)\\ &= 2 (x_i - z_i) + \lambda\textrm{sign}(z_i) \end{align}$$

However, when we set $\nabla \phi_i = 0$, we see that there can be a sign disagreement. When we find $\widehat{x}_i$ by setting $\nabla \phi_i = 0$, we find that $\widehat{x}_i = -\frac{\lambda}{2}\textrm{sign}(z_i) + z_i$. When $|z_i| < \frac{\lambda}{2}$, $\textrm{sign}(x_i) \not = \textrm{sign}(x_i)$. This is the assumption we started out with, and it has to be made true. To make it true, we set

$$\widehat{x}_i = \textrm{sign}(z_i) \left( |z| - \lambda/2 \right)_+$$

Prox gradient method for LASSO¶

We have shown above that

$$\textrm{prox}_\lambda(z) = \textrm{sign}(z) \cdot \left(|z| - \lambda/2\right)$$

and we know that for the least squares loss,

$$\nabla L(x) = A^T (Ax - y)$$

Therefore, we can optimize this function by iterating over

$$\begin{align} z &= x_k - \nabla L(x_k)\\ x_{k+1} &= \textrm{prox}_\lambda(z) \end{align}$$

Main lab¶

Elastic Net In Practice¶

Within this lab, we will be performing classification on subjects from an fMRI dataset known as starplus. The predict whether patients had just seen a picture or sentence from the neural activity measured over a period of time after each stimuli was imparted. We have preprocessed the scans from 6 subjects and included this dataset in fMRIGroup.mat. Download this file and inspect the contents. You will see a struct containing information for 6 subjects. Each struct contains an 80 element label vector, an 80x~5000 design matrix, and a 25x~5000 boolean roi matrix containing boolean indices defining features belonging to regions of interest in the brain. For the purposes of this lab, you will only need to use the data from a single subject. You could choose from any of the 6 subjects, but we strongly suggest that you use subject 2.

To evaluate the performance of your classifiers in this lab, we recommend using the following cross validation protocol:

  1. Select a series of regularization parameters $\lambda$ which span a range of reasonable values ie. $1e-4$ to $1e4$.
  2. Split your training data into ten folds of equal size. With such a small sample size, you may want to make sure your label distribution within each fold is equal (see this link to make this easier).
  3. Set one of the folds aside as a hold-out set.
  4. Use 8 of the remaining folds as training data, and train a classifier for each choice of regularization parameter $\lambda$.
  5. Evaluate the accuracy of these classifiers using the 1 remaining test data fold.
  6. Repeat steps 3&4 9 times (once for each possible test set) and average the results.
  7. Use the regularization parameter $\lambda$ that yielded the highest average prediction accuracy to train a classifier using all 9 of these folds.
  8. Evaluate the accuracy of the classifier from step 6 on the hold out fold.
  9. Repeat steps 2-7 10 times (once for each choice of hold-out set) and average the results.

Group Lasso¶

In certain situations, we may believe that the features in our data set belong to groups and the signal we are looking for is contained within a sparse subset of these groups. Furthermore, we may assume that the the elements active groups have minimum energy. Assumptions like these are common in applications such as genomic --only a sparse subset of gene pathways are implicated in certain disorders-- and fMRI analysis be -- only a few functional regions of the brain are active in encoding certain types of information.

We can formulate these types of assumptions in the form of an optimization problem. We’d like to minimize the error while only distributing our feature weights among a sparse subset of pre-defined groups. As discussed in the introduction, we know that the $\ell_1$ norm encourages sparsity and the $\ell_2$ norm encourages low-energy within the recovered signal. The properties of these regularization terms can be leveraged to enforce a new type of regularization:

We’d like to minimize the number of active groups where the "activation level" or energy contained within a single group can be written as $||x_{g_i}|| \in \mathbb{R}$. Since the output of this term is a non-negative scalar, we can define a new vector:

$$w_G = \begin{bmatrix} ||x_{g_1}|| \\ ||x_{g_2}|| \\ \vdots \\ ||x_{g_{|G|}}|| \end{bmatrix} $$

Where $|G|$ is the total number of groups. Now, we can use what we have learned about the properties of the $\ell_1$ norm to encourage only a small subset of these terms to be non-zero:

$$\widehat{x} = \arg \min_{x} \, L(X) +\lambda ||w_G||_1$$

Because the $\ell_1$ norm is over the vector of group energies, only a sparse subset of the original of groups will be activated. As each of the terms in the vector $w_G$ is guaranteed to be non-negative (by the properties of norms) we can rewrite this problem as:

$$\widehat{x} = \arg \min_{x} \, L(X) + \lambda\sum_{g \in G} ||x_g||_2$$

Where $G$ is the set of groups we have defined from our original feature set, and $x_g$ denotes the feature vector containing only the features defined as belonging to set $g$. This process is known as the $\ell_1/\ell_2$ or group lasso regularization, because it is an $\ell_1$ norm of $\ell_2$ norms and encourages group sparsity.

The group lasso can be implemented using a proximal gradient method as described in the background section. To do this, we will need to select a differentiable loss term that makes sense for the problem we are solving. Next, we will need to implement the $\ell_{2-1}$ prox operator. This prox operator , referred to as "group" or "block" soft-thresholding, is defined as:

$$ \textrm{prox}_\lambda(x)_g = (1 - \frac{\lambda}{||x_g||_2^2})_+ x_g $$

This operator is very similar to the soft-thresholding operator we are already using to perform $\ell_1$, but is performed once for each group feature vector $x_g$ as opposed to once for each feature $x_i$.

Sparse Group LASSO¶

In certain situations, assumptions of group sparsity may not be adequate to capture the true structure of our data. As you hopefully saw in the last experiment, $\ell_1/\ell_2$ regularization tends to select entire groups of features. In many applications, including fMRI analysis, we may actually believe that a sparse subset of feature groups are active AND the activity within those groups is sparse. To model these assumptions, we will need to augment our original $\ell_1/\ell_2$ regularization term. This can be achieved by combining regularization terms:

$$ \widehat{x} = \arg \min_x \, L(x) + \lambda ((1-\alpha)\sum_{g \in G} ||x_g||_2 + \alpha||x||_1) \hspace{1em} \alpha \in [0,1] $$

This new term,known as the Sparse Group LASSO Regularization, will uncover a sparse signal within a sparse subset of feature groups. This propert arises from teh fact that now $\ell_1$ regularization is being performed between features belonging to separate feature groups while elastic net regularization is occuring betweenThis type of structure is referred to as Group Sparse & Sparse. This new regularization term can be implemented by combining the prox operators for the $\ell_1$ and $\ell_1/\ell_2$ in the same way that elastic nets combines the prox operators for the $\ell_1$ and $\ell_2$ norms.
